# normal image arrange matrix
array_spectrum = np.array([np.arange(0, 255, 17),
                           np.arange(0, 255, 17),
                           np.arange(0, 255, 17),
                           np.arange(0, 255, 17)])

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))

# arrange function
ax[0].imshow(array_spectrum, cmap='gray')
ax[0].set_title('Arange_Function')

# transpose function
ax[1].imshow(array_spectrum.T, cmap='gray')
ax[1].set_title('Transpose_Function')

plt.show()

In [22]:
# Open the image
image = Image.open(r"C:\Users\navin\Downloads\puppy.jpg")

# Convert the image to numpy array
image_array = np.array(image)

# Split the image into its red, green, and blue channels
red_channel = image_array[:, :, 0]
green_channel = image_array[:, :, 1]
blue_channel = image_array[:, :, 2]

# Create a figure and axes for displaying the images horizontally
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))

# Display the red, green, and blue channels
axes[0].imshow(red_channel, cmap='Reds')
axes[0].set_title('Red Channel')

axes[1].imshow(green_channel, cmap='Greens')
axes[1].set_title('Green Channel')

axes[2].imshow(blue_channel, cmap='Blues')
axes[2].set_title('Blue Channel')

# Hide the axes
for ax in axes:
    ax.axis('off')

# Display the images
plt.show()

hsv_image = cv2.cvtColor(original_image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)

# Split the HSV image into three channels: Hue, Saturation, and Value
hue, saturation, value = cv2.split(hsv_image)

# Display the three channels horizontally
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))

# Display the Hue channel
axes[0].imshow(hue, cmap='hsv')
axes[0].set_title('Hue')

axes[1].set_title('Saturation')

# Display the Value channel
axes[2].imshow(value, cmap='hsv')
axes[2].set_title('Value')

# Remove the axis labels
for ax in axes:
    ax.axis('off')

In [30]:
# Get the dimensions of the image
width, height = image.size

# Calculate the dimensions for the three parts
part_width = width // 3

# Define the regions for the three parts
part1 = (0, 0, part_width, height)
part2 = (part_width, 0, 2 * part_width, height)
part3 = (2 * part_width, 0, width, height)

# Crop the image into three parts
image_part1 = image.crop(part1)
image_part2 = image.crop(part2)
image_part3 = image.crop(part3)

# Convert images to grayscale
image_part1_gray = image_part1.convert("L")
image_part2_gray = image_part2.convert("L")
image_part3_gray = image_part3.convert("L")

# Convert images to binary
threshold = 128
image_part1_binary = image_part1_gray.point(lambda p: p > threshold and 255)
image_part2_binary = image_part2_gray.point(lambda p: p > threshold and 255)
image_part3_binary = image_part3_gray.point(lambda p: p > threshold and 255)

# Convert images to numpy arrays
image_part1_array = np.array(image_part1_binary)
image_part2_array = np.array(image_part2_binary)
image_part3_array = np.array(image_part3_binary)

# Display images horizontally
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))

axes[0].imshow(image_part1_array, cmap='gray')
axes[0].axis('off')
axes[0].set_title('Part 1')

axes[1].imshow(image_part2_array, cmap='gray')
axes[1].axis('off')
axes[1].set_title('Part 2')

axes[2].imshow(image_part3_array, cmap='gray')
axes[2].axis('off')
axes[2].set_title('Part 3')

plt.show()
